Description:

  Table 1 shows the main characteristics of the 13,888 study participants with current wheeze and never wheeze. We use stars to show the level of significance. * P < .05 and ** P < .01 for the comparison of subjects with current wheeze and never wheeze.

  Compared with the 11,767 control subjects, the 2,121 subjects with current wheeze were more likely to be older, female, non-Hispanic white, current smokers, and users of oral or inhaled steroids in the previous 2 days; and to have a household income less than $20,000, a family history of asthma, vitamin D insufficiency, occupational exposure to mineral dusts or exhaust fumes, a higher BMI, a higher serum cotinine level, higher levels of serum cadmium and lead, a higher FeNO, and lower FEV1, FVC, and FEV1/FVC.

The Process of Getting Table 1

Firstly we use svydesign function which specify a complex survey design to clear the data, recode the index and have a general understanding of it.

Take the index about health insurance coverage as an example.

#example:insurance coverage
#table(data1$HIQ011)
tmp_blood$HIQ011[which(tmp_blood$HIQ011 == 9)] <- NA
tmp_blood$HIQ011[which(tmp_blood$HIQ011 == 7)] <- NA
tmp_blood$HIQ011[which(tmp_blood$HIQ011 == 2)] <- 0
# recode insurance converage 
tmp_blood$HIQ011 <- as.factor(as.character(tmp_blood$HIQ011))
#The svydesign object combines a data frame and all the survey design information needed to analyse it. These objects are used by the survey modelling and summary functions. 
design.WTMEC2YR <- svydesign(ids = ~SDMVPSU, strata = ~SDMVSTRA, weights = ~WTMEC5YR, nest = TRUE, data = tmp_blood)
dsub <- subset(design.WTMEC2YR, ((tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR >= 20) 
                                 & (tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR <= 79) 
                                 & (!is.na(tmp_blood$asthma)) 
                                 & (!is.na(tmp_blood$LBXBCD)) 
                                 & (!is.na(tmp_blood$LBXBPB)))) 
data1 <- tmp_blood[which((tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR >= 20) 
                         & (tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR <= 79) 
                         & (!is.na(tmp_blood$asthma))
                         & (!is.na(tmp_blood$LBXBCD)) 
                         & (!is.na(tmp_blood$LBXBPB))), ] 

#table(data1$HIQ011[which(data1$asthma == 0)])
#table(data1$HIQ011[which(data1$asthma == 1)])

tbl <- svytable(~ asthma + HIQ011, dsub)

In addition, we use svymean and svyttest function to compute the means, variances, ratios and totals for the complex surveys’s data.

Take the index about lung function as an example.

library(sjPlot)

Description:

  Table 2 shows the serum level of cadmium or lead and current wheeze in adults (20≤ age≤79 years).

  In the multivariate analyses of serum cadmium, per 1 unit (ug/L) increase in continuous measurement of serum cadmium is associated with 1.6 times increased odds of current wheeze.

  The odds of current wheeze increased across quartiles of serum cadmium (P for trend < 0.01) and the 4th quartile was significantly associated with more than twofold increased odds of current wheeze.

  In the multivariate models of serum lead, no significant result was found in continuous measurement of lead, whereas the 4th quartile of lead was significantly associated with approximately 1.3 times increased odds.

Figure 1

Boxplots of Lung Function for Quartiles

Description：

  Boxplots of lung function for quartiles of cadmium and quartiles of lead in adults (20 ≤age ≤ 79 years). It shows the distribution of percent predicted FEV1 and percent predicted FEV1/FVC across the quartiles of serum cadmium(A) or lead(B). (* P< 0.05 and ** P< 0.01 for comparison with Q1.)

  For the quartiles of cadmium, percent predicted FEV1 and percent predicted FEV1/FVC were significantly lower in the 3rd and 4th quartiles. (percent predicted FEV1: P< 0.05, P< 0.01;percent predicted FEV1/FVC: P< 0.01)

  For the quartiles of lead, all parameters demonstrated a decreased trend across the 2nd, 3rd and 4th quartiles.

The Process of Ploting

Secondly, we can obtain model fitted FEV1 or FEV1/FVC against cadmium or lead quartile by t-test comparions with FEV1 or FEV1/FVC and quantiles for cadmium or lead to have marks on the plot.

Take comparions with Q1 and Q2 of cadmium as an example.

##t test was used to compare lung function between the 2nd, 3rd or 4th quartiles and the 1st quartile.
#Q1 VS Q2
t.test(data1$fev1_fitted[which(data1$LBXBCD_q == 0)], data1$fev1_fitted[which(data1$LBXBCD_q == 1)])

## t = -1.46, df = 5390.4, p-value = 0.1443

Lastly, we can fit boxplots of lung function [model fitted value] against quartiles for cadmium or lead.

Still take model fitted FEV1 against quartiles for cadmium as an example.

##Change labels of 'LBXBCD_q'

#Change data format into numeric
tmp_blood$LBXBCD_q <- as.numeric(as.character(tmp_blood$LBXBCD_q))
#Replace LBXBCD_q with NA when LBXBCD is NA
tmp_blood$LBXBCD_q[which(is.na(tmp_blood$LBXBCD))] <- NA
#Set breaks
breaks=c(0,0.22,0.34,0.62,max(tmp_blood$LBXBCD[!is.na(tmp_blood$LBXBCD)]))
#Replace LBXBCD_q with "Q1" when LBXBCD is less than 0.22; "Q2" when LBXBCD is no less than 0.22 but less than 0.34;"Q3" when LBXBCD is no less than 0.34 but less than 0.62;"Q4" when LBXBCD is no less than 0.62
tmp_blood$LBXBCD_q=factor(cut(tmp_blood$LBXBCD,breaks,c('Q1','Q2','Q3','Q4')))

##Design for sampling
design.WTMEC2YR <- svydesign(ids = ~SDMVPSU, strata = ~SDMVSTRA, weights = ~WTMEC5YR, nest = TRUE, data = tmp_blood)
#Adults(20≤ age≤79 years)
dsub <- subset(design.WTMEC2YR, ((tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR >= 20) 
                                 & (tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR <= 79) 
                                 & (!is.na(tmp_blood$asthma))))
data1 <- tmp_blood[which((tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR >= 20) 
                         & (tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR <= 79) 
                         & (!is.na(tmp_blood$asthma))), ]
#Lung function [model fitted value] against quartiles

Description:

  Table 4 shows the serum level of cadmium and lead and lung function in adults, stratified by smoking status and current wheeze status. (* P < .05 and ** P < .01 for comparison with Q1.)

  In never or former smokers, every 1-unit increment in log10(serum cadmium) was significantly associated with approximately 3.2 and 3.6 reduction in percent predicted FEV1 and percent predicted FEV1/FVC. Similar trends were found among never or former smokers with or without wheeze.

  Current smokers showed the similar but more pronounced decline in lung function. For serum lead, we found that every 1-unit increment in log10(serum lead) was significantly associated with approximately 2.4 reduction in percent predicted FEV1 and 2.9 reduction in predicted FEV1/FVC among never or former smokers.

  The significant decreasing pattern of lung function was also found in other strata of never or former smokers and among current smokers.

The Process of Getting Table 4

Firstly, we apply svyglm function to the model, which fit a generalised linear model to data from the survey design, with inverse-probability weighting and design-based standard errors.

Take participants who had never smoked or had smoked and who were not asthmatic as an example.

e-Figure 1

Odds Ratio Plot of Cadmium or Lead Level and Wheeze

Description:

  It shows the effect of serum cadmium and lead on whether had an asthma in adults, by presenting different odds ratios with their confidence intervals among different levels of metal_75. (* P< 0.05, **P< 0.01)

  Considering the levels of serum cadmium and lead, adults with high cadmium and low lead and those with both high cadmium and high lead showed approximately 2.0 to 2.5 times increased risk of current wheeze.

The Process of Ploting

Firstly, we need to create a variable metal_75.

Metal_75 including four levels:

  (1) Low Cadmium and low Lead;

  (2) Low Cadmium and high Lead;

  (3) High Cadmium and low Lead;

  (4) High Cadmium and high Lead.

##create a variable metal_75
#Replace metal_75 with NA when LBXBPB or LBXBCD is NA
tmp_blood$metal_75[is.na(tmp_blood$LBXBPB)|is.na(tmp_blood$LBXBCD)] <- NA

library(dplyr)

tmp_blood <- tmp_blood %>%
  mutate(metal_75 = ifelse(tmp_blood$LBXBCD <= 0.62,
#Low cadmium and low lead:When LBXBCD is no more than 0.62 and LBXBPB is no more than 2, replace metal_75 with 0
#Low cadmium and high lead:When LBXBCD is no more than 0.62 and LBXBPB is more than 2, replace metal_75 with 1
                           ifelse(tmp_blood$LBXBPB <= 2,0,1),
#High cadmium and low lead:When LBXBCD is more than 0.62 and LBXBPB is no more than 2, replace metal_75 with 2
#High cadmium and high lead:When LBXBCD is more than 0.62 and LBXBPB is more than 2, replace metal_75 with 3
                           ifelse(tmp_blood$LBXBPB <= 2,2,3)))

#Change data format into factor
tmp_blood$metal_75 <- as.factor(as.character(tmp_blood$metal_75))

Secondly, we need to fit the Generalized Linear Model(GLM) and calculate odds ratios.

library(sjPlot)

Lastly,we can do ploting.

Still take the fitting model of FEV1 as an example.

#Core wrapping function
wrap.it <- function(x, len)
{ 
  sapply(x, function(y) paste(strwrap(y, len), 
                              collapse = "\n"), 
         USE.NAMES = FALSE)
}

#Call this function with a list or vector
wrap.labels <- function(x, len)
{
  if (is.list(x))
  {
    lapply(x, wrap.it, len)
  } else {
    wrap.it(x, len)
  }
}

labels <- c("Low Cadmium and low Lead (N = 8456)", 
            "Low Cadmium and high Lead (N = 2032)", 
            "High Cadmium and low Lead (N = 2065)", 
            "High Cadmium and high Lead (N = 1345)")

wr.lap <- wrap.labels(labels, 21)

#Design for sampling
#Adults(20≤ age≤79 years)
design.WTMEC2YR <- svydesign(ids = ~SDMVPSU, strata = ~SDMVSTRA, weights = ~WTMEC5YR, nest = TRUE, data = tmp_blood)
dsub <- subset(design.WTMEC2YR, ((tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR >= 20) 
                                 & (tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR <= 79) 
                                 & (!is.na(tmp_blood$asthma)) 
                                 & (!is.na(tmp_blood$metal_75))))

#Boxplot
p <- svyboxplot(fev1_fitted_75 ~ metal_75, 
                design = subset(design.WTMEC2YR, ((tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR >= 20) & (tmp_blood$RIDAGEYR <= 79) & (!is.na(tmp_blood$asthma)) & (!is.na(tmp_blood$metal_75)))),
                all.outliers = TRUE, 
                na.rm = TRUE, 
                varwidth = TRUE, 
                names = wr.lap, 
                ylab = "Fitted % predicted FEV1", main = "(A)")
